# Run the following JS from JIRA when not logged into JIRA:
{code}
jQuery.ajax({
  type: 'POST',
  url: AJS.contextPath() + "/rest/api/2/field",
  data: JSON.stringify({"name":"Jack","searcherKey":"com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:multiselectsearcher","type":"com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:multicheckboxes"}),
  dataType: "json",
  contentType: "application/json"
});
{code}
# (BUG) The response will be a 400. I would expect a 401 for an anonymous user and 403 for a logged in user.

# Run the following JS from JIRA when logged into JIRA as an admin but without WebSudo authenticated for that user:
{code}
jQuery.ajax({
  type: 'POST',
  url: AJS.contextPath() + "/rest/api/2/field",
  data: JSON.stringify({"name":"Jack","searcherKey":"com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:multiselectsearcher","type":"com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:multicheckboxes"}),
  dataType: "json",
  contentType: "application/json"
});
{code}
# (BUG) You will get a 20x response and the field will be created. I would expect some kind of 401 websudo error.

# Run the following JS from JIRA when logged into JIRA:
{code}
jQuery.ajax({
  type: 'POST',
  url: AJS.contextPath() + "/rest/api/2/field",
  data: JSON.stringify({"name":"","searcherKey":"","type":"com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:multicheckboxes"}),
  dataType: "json",
  contentType: "application/json"
});
{code}
# (BUG) You will get a response like:
{code}
{"errorMessages":[],"errors":{"fieldName":"You must specify a name for this custom field."}}
{code}

The error on the "name" is returned in the "fieldName". The error for "searcherKey" will be returned in "searcher". I would expect the request and response fields to match up. For example:

{code}
{"errorMessages":[],"errors":{"name":"You must specify a name for this custom field."}}
{code}

